(69, 7, 6, NULL, 'Havoc in UNN male hostel - Alvan Ikoku hostel', '\n<p>\n   It was exactly about 5:17pm yesterday evening when it started to rain.  The rain was accompanied by a heavy wind which eventually removed the roof of the giant hostel. It was later gathered that no one was hurt or being killed by the unforeseen incidence.\n</p>\n', '2018-05-04 03:14:56', 0, 'APPROVED', 177314),
(79, 7, 6, NULL, 'Private universities in Nigeria and their tuition fees', '\n<p>\n   List of private universities in Nigeria and their fees:\r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   \r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   American University of Nigeria in Yola. It is the most expensive private university in Nigeria. Amount of school fees is 1,590,000 NGN.\r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   \r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   Achievers University. This university is located in Owo, South-West Nigeria. By comparing private universities in Nigeria and their school fees, Achievers University more cost-effective than others. You need to pay 420, 000 NGN.\r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   \r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   Babcock University. It is one of the oldest private university in Nigeria that was established in 1999 and located in Ilishan-Remo. Amount of school fees varies from 620,000 NGN to 3,000,000 NGN.\r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   \r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   Bowen University in Iwo. This university was founded in 2002 by Nigerian Baptist Convention. Amount of school fees is 700,000 NGN.\r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   \r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   Redeemerâ€™s University. The school is located in Redemption city. You need to pay 605,000 NGN for Natural Sciense; 545,000 NGN for Humanities; 575,000 NGN for Management Science.\r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   \r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   Caritas University. Caritas Uni is located in Enugu. Amount of school fees varies from 248,000 NGN to 398,000 NGN for Management and Social Sciencies; from 298,000 NGN to 450,000 NGN for Faculty of Engineering; from 248,000 NGN to 398,000 NGN for Natural Sciencies.\r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   \r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   Gregory University. This university was established in 2012 in Uturu. Tuition fees depend on department: Social Sciencies: 420,000 NGN, Medical courses: 600,000 NGN, Engineering courses: 500,000 NGN.\r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   \r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   Benson Idahosa University. BIU was founded in 2002 and named after the popular Christian evangelist. School fees: 500,000 NGN.\r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   \r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   Caleb University. School fees: 505,000 NGN.\r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   \r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   Chrisland University. It is one of the youngest private university in Nigeria that was established in 2015 and is located in Olabisi. School fees: 405,000 NGN.\r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   \r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   Igbinedion University. The school is situated in Okada. It is also one of the oldest private university in Nigeria that was established in 1999. School fees: 643,000 NGN.\n</p>\n', '2018-05-04 13:08:32', 0, 'APPROVED', 177908),
(95, 7, 6, NULL, '26 out of 26,637 LASU students graduate with first class', '\n<p>\n   Lagos State University (LASU) has said 26 out of the 26,637 students billed to graduate during its 22nd convocation would bag first class honours.\r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   \r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   The vice chancellor of the institution, Professor Olanrewaju Fagbohun, announced this in Lagos on Monday, May 7 at the media briefing heralding the universityâ€™s convocation.\r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   \r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   It was reports that the convocation would hold on May 23 and 24 at the university campus, Ojo, along the Badagry Expressway, NAN reports.\r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   \r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   It wasÂ noted that Fagbohun said that the best graduating student for the 2017/2018 academic session, whose name and the department are still withheld, recorded a Cumulative Grade Point Aggregate (CGPA) of 4.7.\n</p>\n', '2018-05-08 06:45:42', 0, 'APPROVED', 183285),
(109, 7, 6, '109.jpg', 'No more tuition fees in Federal Universities: FEC considers fees illegal', '\n<p>\n   The Federal Executive Council (FEC) will scrutinize reports of federal universities charging tuition fees from students as it is illegal and against the law.\r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   \r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   Anthony Anwuka, The Minister of State for Education, stated this while briefing State House correspondents on the result of the council meeting presided over by Yemi Osinbajo the Vice President on Wednesday, that government will investigate the matter.\r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   \r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   He observed that there are accusations that some of the institutions are pricing students per course unit, which he said is illegal and must be stopped immediately.\r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   \r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   Ankuwa stated thatâ€œNo federal university should charge tuition fees. That is the law. And, we understand some universities now charge fees per course unit and we are going to make sure that we investigate that properly and make it stops.\r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   \r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   â€œBut students can pay other auxiliary fees but not in excess. Various university councils and management should be able to fix what fees students should pay that is affordable and acceptable to the students. That is the position.\r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   \r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   â€œThe federal government does not determine fees for private and state universities. They only take responsibility for fees paid in the federal universities.â€\r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   \r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   He revealed that the council also approved the license for a new university in Kano, Skyline University, Kano.\n</p>\n', '2018-05-10 14:53:50', 0, 'APPROVED', 186653),
(111, 7, 6, NULL, 'Minister canvasses one year re-schooling for Nigerian fresh graduates', '\n<p>\n   The minister of state for education, Professor Anthony Anwukah, has put forward a proposal for Nigerian students to spend an extra year in specialised institutions after graduation.\r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   \r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   Professor Anwukah\'s proposal was tabled at the ongoing retreat for Governing Councils of Nigerian Federal Universities, organised by the National Universities Commission (NUC) with the theme,Â â€œElements of Statutory Governance, Procurement and Financial Accounting in Nigerian Universities.â€\r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   \r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   He said the suggestion was being made because many university graduates were not good enough to be employed by industries.\n</p>\n', '2018-05-11 12:14:23', 0, 'APPROVED', 187934),
(113, 7, 6, NULL, 'FG fires NECO registrar, 2 deputy directors', '\n<p>\n   The registrar of the National Examinations Council (NECO), Professor Charles Uwakwe and two deputy directors of the examination body have been sacked.\r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   \r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   The Nation reports that though no official reason has been given for the disengagement of the register, the two deputy directors might have been disengaged for alleged corrupt practices.\r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   \r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   Some sources attributed the sack of the registrar to the award of a N25 billion contract which was without the knowledge of either the federal ministry of education or the governing board of the council.\n</p>\n', '2018-05-13 14:14:37', 0, 'APPROVED', 190934),
(115, 7, 6, NULL, '22-year-old Nigerian-born Elizabeth Bright elected as the youngest Councillor in the United Kingdom', '\n<p>\n   A 22-year-old UK-based Nigerian student, Elizabeth Bright has made history after being elected as a Councillor representing Eastbrook and in dagenham, United kingdom. Bright emerged winner on May 4 after a rigorous election process and nights of planning.\r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   \r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   Interestingly, Her mother, Councillor Afolasade Bright from the Borough of Barking and Dagenham Council was also re-elected. She is also a former speaker/civic mayor London borough of Hackney.\r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   \r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   Elizabeth shared photos from her victorious moment on social media, attributing her success to god while thanking all her supporters and volunteers who sacrificed a lot for her to achieve her goal.\n</p>\n', '2018-05-14 10:16:53', 0, 'APPROVED', 192136),
(118, 7, 6, NULL, 'Gov Ugwuanyi grants scholarship to 340 indigent students of state&rsquo;s Polytechnic, inaugurates S', '\n<p>\n   Governor Ugwuanyi explained that 20 indigent students in each of the 17 L.G.As will benefit from the scholarship scheme, which will cover their tuition fees for four years of study at a total cost of N41.6 million.\r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   \r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   The governor spoke during the maiden engineering day commemoration at the institution, where he inaugurated the newly constructed School of Engineering Complex sponsored by Prince Arthur Eze and laid foundation for the construction of Prof. Julius Onah School of Management Technology.\n</p>\n', '2018-05-15 13:23:08', 0, 'APPROVED', 193763),
(126, 7, 6, '126.jpg', 'NANS Threaten to Close UNN Over Death of a Student', '\n<p>\n   Tension mounts at the university of Nigeria, Nsukka as the National Association of Nigerian Students (NANS) has allegedly theatened to shut down the university over the death of a student outside the university community.\r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   \r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   Vanguard gathered that the deceased student whose identity could not be ascertained as at the time of filling this report was said to be residing at Odenigwe a nearby community to the university before his death.\r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   \r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   An authoritative source at the university who would not want his name in print confided in Vanguard that an exco of NANS spoke to the acting chief security officer (CSO) on phone, threatening that they would come from Abuja to shut down the university over the death of a student.\n</p>\n', '2018-05-16 13:31:05', 0, 'APPROVED', 195211),
(136, 4, 6, '136.jpg', 'Final Verdict - Jamb to conduct another examination', '\n<p>\n   JAMB sets May 26 for rescheduled examinations for over 12,000 candidates\r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   \r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   21 MAY 2018\r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   \r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   The Joint Admissions and Matriculation Board (JAMB) on Sunday said that it had set May 26 for rescheduled Unified Tertiary Matriculation Examinations (UTME) for more than 12, 000 candidates across the country.\r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   \r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   The Boardâ€™s Head of Media, Dr Fabian Benjamin, disclosed this in an interview with the News Agency of Nigeria (NAN) in Abuja.\r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   \r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   According to Benjamin, more than 12, 000 candidates are expected to sit for the mop up examinations in few of its centres across the country.\r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   \r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   This category of candidates, he explained, are those whose biometrics were not  captured during the initial period of the UTME in March.\r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   \r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   He said: â€œâ€œIt would also include those, who are yet to see their results since the end of the examinations in March till date and have not been involved in any form of malpractice.\r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   â€œ\r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   \r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   â€œIt will also include those, who were unable to print out their e-slip before the earlier examinations and those whose centres were cancelled for suspected malpractices.â€™â€™\r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   \r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   According to him, â€œthere are centres that were cancelled because of suspicious activities but the board was unable to identify the actual culprits.\r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   \r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   However, he said that those, who were involved and caught in illicit acts and centres where a case of malpractice has been established against them would not partake in the rescheduled examinations.\r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   \r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   He advised  candidates, who might have fallen into any of the categories qualified for the examination to print their e-slips from Monday, May 21.\r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   \r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   NAN recalls the board had earlier promised to reschedule the examinations for some candidates whose cases were exceptional, adding that candidates, who fall under such categories would be contacted before then. \r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   \r\n</p>\n\n<p>\n   #GodOverEverything\n</p>\n', '2018-05-22 07:41:11', 0, 'APPROVED', 203501);
